The expression {x for x in ‘abc’} is a set comprehension that creates a set of individual characters from the string ‘abc’, resulting in {‘a’, ‘b’, ‘c’} (order may vary due to the unordered nature of sets). The expression {x*3 for x in ‘abc’} multiplies each character by 3, producing ‘aaa’, ‘bbb’, and ‘ccc’, and collects them into a set: {‘aaa’, ‘bbb’, ‘ccc’}.
So the output will be:
    {‘a’, ‘b’, ‘c’}
   {‘aaa’, ‘bbb’, ‘ccc’}

